The capital asset pricing model (CAPM) is as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{r }_{I}&={\text{Risk-Free Interest Rate + }{B}_{I}}{\text{ $\times$ Market Risk Premium}}
\end{aligned}$$

Where: 
$$\begin{aligned}
{\text{r}_{I}}& = {\text{Cost of capital for an investment}} \\
{\text{B}_{I}} &= {\text{Beta}} 
\end{aligned}$$

First, let us determine whether Stock Y is correctly priced. Let us insert the provided data to the formula from step 4 and determine that the stock's expected return is correct. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{r }_{I}&={\text{2.4\% + }{1.2}}{\text{ $\times$ 7.2\%}}\\
&={\textbf{11.04\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The expected return of Stock Y must be 11.04%.**

Next, let us also determine the expected return of Stock Z. We will use the process we made on step 5. The expected return of Stock Z is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{r }_{I}&={\text{2.4\% + }{0.80}}{\text{ $\times$ 7.2\%}}\\
&={\textbf{8.16\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The expected return of Stock Z must be 8.16%.**
